2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   **Title:** AsciiJSON silently corrupts non-BMP characters (emoji) by emitting malformed \u escapes
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   **Labels:** none
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   ### Body
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   ### Description
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   `render.AsciiJSON` corrupts any Unicode code point above U+FFFF (non-BMP characters such as emoji). It escapes every non-ASCII rune with `fmt.Appendf(buf, "\\u%04x", r)`, but `%04x` is a *minimum* width, not a fixed width. A non-BMP rune needs 5+ hex digits, so a single 5-digit `\uXXXXX` token is written. JSON `\u` escapes are **exactly 4 hex digits**, so a decoder reads the first 4 as one character and the trailing digit(s) as literal text.
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   The output is still *syntactically valid* JSON (so this is not a parse error and is easy to miss), but the value is silently wrong — it does not round-trip.
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   Per RFC 8259 §7, code points outside the BMP must be encoded as a UTF-16 surrogate pair (e.g. U+1F600 → `\ud83d\ude00`).
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   **Example — `😀` (U+1F600):**
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   | | value |
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   |---|---|
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   | Input | `😀` |
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   | `AsciiJSON` output | `{"msg":"\u1f600"}` |
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   | After `json.Unmarshal` | `ὠ0`  (U+1F60 `ὠ` + literal `0`) |
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   | Expected after round-trip | `😀` |
2026-06-04 13:55:14,353 | DEBUG    |   
2026-06-04 13:55:14,354 | DEBUG    |   Offending code — `render/json.go` (`AsciiJSON.Render`):
